s. Too often, the assumptions that underlie the prevailing theory and practice of addressing major political and economic problems remain unquestioned, with economic and political conflicts displaced into issues of administration and leadership. Ventriss calls for a reinvigorated notion of publicness based, in part, on a public social science, civic experimentation, and policies designed and tailored to the unique needs of various publics. As a way to move forward, this book offers ideas for redefining professionalism, promoting civic initiatives, and rethinking professional education for public service.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracy. 0aGovernment accountability. 0aPublic administrationxCitizen participation. 0aPublic administrationxEvaluation. 0aPublic administrationxMoral and ethical aspects. 4aPolitics and Law : Democracy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPublic Policy : Public Administration. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Affairs & Administration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848126540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438481265423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438481265/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles